<TITLE> 'AL will pass no law in conflict with Quran' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 13 (bdnews24.com) Awami League will not enact any law that conflicts with the teachings of the Quran or Sunnah, said a senior Awami League figure on Saturday. "Awami League will not pass any law that goes against the Quran and the Sunnah. We want to establish the magnanimity of Islam as a religion of peace. At the same time, we want to ensure so that all can pursue their respective religions," said AL presidium member Motia Chowdhury. "On the eve of election, many have started using the name of the holy religion of Islam  We do not want religion to be used as political weapon." Inaugurating the party's media centre, she told reporters: "I hope bond between journalists and the Awami League will be firm. I request you to see our failings, if any, with a spirit of graciousness, and disseminate information in a positive way." On the party's election pledges unveiled Friday by the pary president, Motia said: "The manifesto carries the dream of a bright future for the next generation." "[Sheikh Hasina] also promised freedom of the media and independent journalism." The AL president could not inaugurate the media centre on account of illness, Motia said. "Sheikh Hasina has been suffering from fever since morning." Co-chairman of AL's election steering committee, HT Imam said, "This media centre will disseminate all news about Awami League and the grand alliance." bdnews
